Radiation detection cannot be performed directly by mobile phones or TVs using HTML and JavaScript alone 
because these devices do not contain dedicated radiation-sensing hardware such as Geiger–Müller tubes or
dosimeters. The HTML code provided serves as a user interface that can either simulate radiation readings
for demonstration and educational purposes or display real radiation data received from an external sensor. 
In the simulation version, JavaScript generates random values that mimic radiation levels and updates them 
on the screen at regular intervals. In the real-sensor version, the application uses technologies such as 
the Web Bluetooth API to connect to a compatible external radiation detector and display actual measurements. 
While this approach is useful for creating monitoring dashboards, educational tools, and IoT-based radiation 
monitoring systems, the accuracy of the readings depends entirely on the external sensor being used. Therefore, 
without specialized radiation-detection hardware, mobile phones and TVs can only simulate radiation measurements
rather than detect real radiation.
